text: 84 F with PMHx of Renovascular HTN c/b NSTEMI now s/p renal stents, Gout and h/o Crohn's disease who presented to the ED on ___ with RLQ pain for approx 2 days. She denies any nausea/vomiting/diarrhea or constipation but has not been taking po well and felt dehydrated.

Patient is a 67-year-old male with history of COPD, CAD s/p CABG in 2015, and type 2 diabetes mellitus who presents with increasing shortness of breath over the past 3 days. He reports productive cough with yellow sputum, low-grade fever, and decreased exercise tolerance. He denies chest pain, palpitations, or lower extremity edema. Home medications include albuterol, fluticasone/salmeterol, metformin, aspirin, and atorvastatin.

45F presents with chest pain radiating to left arm and jaw that started 2 hours ago while at rest. Pain is described as pressure-like, 8/10 in severity. Associated symptoms include diaphoresis and nausea. Patient has history of hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and family history of premature CAD (father had MI at age 48). Current smoker, 1 PPD for 25 years. Vital signs on presentation: BP 165/95, HR 92, RR 18, O2 sat 98% on RA, afebrile.

72-year-old female with history of atrial fibrillation on warfarin, hypertension, and osteoarthritis presenting with acute onset confusion and right-sided weakness. Per family, patient was at her baseline mental status until this morning when she was found to have slurred speech and inability to move her right arm and leg. Last known normal was yesterday evening around 8 PM. No history of prior stroke or TIA. No recent falls or head trauma. Currently taking warfarin, metoprolol, lisinopril, and acetaminophen.

56-year-old male with no significant past medical history presents with 3-day history of abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting. Pain is located in the right upper quadrant, constant, and worsened after meals. Patient reports dark urine and clay-colored stools for the past day. Denies fever or chills. No alcohol use. Physical exam notable for jaundice and RUQ tenderness with positive Murphy's sign. Labs show elevated total bilirubin 4.2, direct bilirubin 3.1, ALT 245, AST 187, alkaline phosphatase 310.
